        <div class="blog-article-body">

            <p class="blog-lead">
                A small firm or solo practice doesn't have an IT department
                or an enterprise document management budget — but the
                documents still need to move through intake, review,
                redaction, signature, and delivery just as reliably as they
                do at a large firm. Here's a workflow built around free,
                task-specific tools instead of one expensive suite.
            </p>

            <h2>1. Intake: get everything into one format</h2>
            <p>
                Client documents arrive as scans, phone photos, Word files,
                and PDFs, often in the same matter folder. Standardize on PDF
                immediately. Convert Word documents with
                <a href="/word-to-pdf">Word to PDF</a> and phone photos of
                documents with <a href="/jpg-to-pdf">JPG to PDF</a>, then
                <a href="/merge-pdf">merge</a> everything related to one
                matter into a single file with a consistent name.
            </p>

            <h2>2. First review: AI contract triage</h2>
            <p>
                Before committing billable attorney time, run incoming
                contracts and agreements through an
                <a href="/review-contract">AI Contract Reviewer</a> for a
                structured first pass — parties, key dates, obligations, and
                clauses worth a closer look. It doesn't replace attorney
                judgment, but it cuts down the time spent on an initial read
                of a routine agreement.
            </p>

            <h2>3. Comparing versions and redlines</h2>
            <p>
                When a redline comes back from opposing counsel, don't read
                it line by line against your last draft. <a href="/compare-pdf">
                PDF Compare</a> produces a word-by-word diff so you can see
                exactly what changed in seconds, and confirm an executed
                document matches what was actually negotiated.
            </p>

            <h2>4. Redacting before anything leaves the firm</h2>
            <p>
                Anything going to opposing counsel, a court filing, or a
                third party should be checked for information that needs to
                be withheld — PII, privileged notes, unrelated client names.
                Use <a href="/redact-pdf">PDF Redaction</a> rather than a
                black box drawn in a viewer; covering text visually doesn't
                remove it from the underlying file, which has caused real
                disclosure incidents at other firms.
            </p>

            <h2>5. Signatures on engagement letters and simple agreements</h2>
            <p>
                Engagement letters, intake forms, and simple agreements
                rarely need a notary or in-person meeting.
                <a href="/sign-pdf">Electronic signature</a> gets these
                signed and returned the same day instead of waiting on
                printing, signing, scanning, and emailing back.
            </p>

            <h2>6. Protecting documents before they leave</h2>
            <p>
                Anything emailed to a client or a third party that contains
                privileged or personal information should be password
                protected with <a href="/lock-pdf">Lock PDF</a>, with the
                password shared over a separate channel — a phone call or
                text, not the same email thread.
            </p>

            <h2>7. Digitizing the paper file</h2>
            <p>
                Older case files and physical documents that get scanned in
                are usually just images — not searchable. Run them through
                <a href="/pdf-ocr">PDF OCR</a> so you can search across a
                case file for a specific clause or name instead of opening
                every document by hand.
            </p>

            <h2>8. Handling volume: batch processing</h2>
            <p>
                Discovery productions and due diligence document sets can
                run into the hundreds of files. <a href="/batch">Batch
                Processing</a> applies one operation — compress, watermark,
                convert — to up to 20 files at once and returns everything
                as a single ZIP, instead of repeating the same steps file by
                file.
            </p>

            <h2>Privacy still matters with smaller volumes</h2>
            <p>
                A solo practice handles the same category of sensitive
                client information as a large firm, just at smaller scale —
                which doesn't make it any less subject to confidentiality
                obligations. Before using any online tool for client
                documents, confirm files are processed securely and deleted
                afterward. PdfToolStack deletes all files within 1 hour and
                never uses document content to train AI models.
            </p>

